  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: e9620f8c34305754d8cc9a7e49e852d9, type: 3}
  m_Name: GlobalGameLocalization_en-US
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_LocaleId:
    m_Code: en-US
  m_SharedData: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 7ee384e42b7e80f459a5b7389591d149, type: 2}
  m_Metadata:
    m_Items: []
  m_TableData:
  - m_Id: 15689658368
    m_Localized: EN test
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 55834391986982912
    m_Localized: EN None
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 92127792197685248
    m_Localized: EN Quiz results
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 92128937733410816
    m_Localized: EN Game results
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 92129047615787008
    m_Localized: EN Minigame results
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 93109690059345920
    m_Localized: Play
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 93109837128421376
    m_Localized: Settings
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 93158983956844544
    m_Localized: Logic gates
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 93159239264129024
    m_Localized: Levels
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 93186492266074112
    m_Localized: Quiz
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 118525458794532864
    m_Localized: Awesome! We did it!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 164636933619306496
    m_Localized: Light up all the bulbs!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 164884267116646400
    m_Localized: Create a binary code!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 164884481839845376
    m_Localized: Now try it without help!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 164884554699100160
    m_Localized: 'Now let''s turn it around: What number do you see right now? Use
      the plus and minus buttons to adjust the value, and when you are sure, press
      the equals button.'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165347498411020288
    m_Localized: Your task will be to set the fan performance so that they cool the
      components just right.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165350384738095104
    m_Localized: If they run too fast, the user will complain about the noise and
      the components will be unnecessarily <color=blue>overcooled (blue).
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165350462869590016
    m_Localized: If they run too slow, the components will <color=red>overheat (red)</color>
      and the computer will slow down.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165350482553458688
    m_Localized: Try to find the ideal setting where the temperature gradually stabilizes
      at the correct value and <color=#0b0>stays in the green zone</color>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165661820018348032
    m_Localized: In this level, we will explore how an HDD (hard drive) actually
      works.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165661930609561600
    m_Localized: We already know that an HDD is more of a 'slow runner' compared
      to a lightning-fast SSD, and in this game, you'll experience that slowness
      firsthand.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165661996279779328
    m_Localized: Your task is to control the drive's <color=#0b0><b>read head</color></b>
      so that its tip exactly catches the squares representing data. Get ready, file
      loading is starting!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165662052739305472
    m_Localized: Watch out, things are getting tougher! We are increasing the drive
      capacity right now.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165671560337281024
    m_Localized: There are differences even among HDDs! This model has a <color=#0b0><b>higher
      RPM</color></b>, so the data flows much faster under the read head. Use this
      performance and <color=#0b0><b>catch them all</color></b>, so we have the file
      loaded in record time!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165672401345564672
    m_Localized: To fit more files into the same area, we need to pack the data much
      closer together.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165709255029673984
    m_Localized: Welcome to the world of SSDs! Forget about slow mechanical heads.
      An SSD works on the principle of electrical impulses.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 165709426505404416
    m_Localized: Your task is to activate the correct <color=#0b0><b>row and column</color></b>
      using the balls on the edge. Where your choices intersect, you will instantly
      read data from the green cell. No waiting, just pure speed!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 166456809505804288
    m_Localized: Welcome to the <color=#0b0><b>CPU</color></b> core! Your task is
      to follow the <color=#0b0><b>instructions</color></b> in the notebook on the
      left and find out if the wizard can conjure his shield.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 166460212755681280
    m_Localized: You can summon data from <color=#0b0><b>RAM</color></b> into the
      processor via the <color=blue><b>blue panel</color></b>. Then you can drag
      them with your mouse into the correct <color=#0b0><b>register (R1-R4)</color></b>
      in the cache.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 166460294875959296
    m_Localized: The colored blocks at the top are used for <color=#0b0><b>calculations</color></b>
      and <color=#0b0><b>comparisons</color></b>. Drag values into the input registers
      so the processor performs the operation you currently need.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 166462323631443968
    m_Localized: You can take the results of operations and move them further between
      <color=#0b0><b>registers</color></b> or send them back to <color=#0b0><b>RAM</color></b>.
      Watch the notebook and follow the instructions exactly!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 166857543216910336
    m_Localized: Welcome to the role of <b>memory manager</b>, your task is to keep
      the system running and ensure the processor never has to wait. <b>Data blocks</b>
      will come to you from the <color=#0b0>HDD/SSD</color>, which you must cleverly
      <color=#0b0><b>store in RAM slots</b></color>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 166859659973087232
    m_Localized: Try to stack the data closely together to <b>save as much space
      as possible</b> for the next packages.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 166859833378197504
    m_Localized: Pay close attention to the <b>CPU</b>, which will continuously request
      specific data using <b>addresses</b>. As soon as you see a request, you must
      <color=#0b0><b>drag the data from RAM</b></color> and deliver it directly to
      the processor.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 166859951946977280
    m_Localized: Some data in memory is no longer needed and just unnecessarily takes
      up precious space. You can therefore <color=#0b0><b>trigger a memory cleanup</b></color>,
      which automatically deletes everything the processor is no longer using.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173922145806733312
    m_Localized: CPU
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173922953180893184
    m_Localized: "Let's try it out \r\nin the game."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173922963524046848
    m_Localized: 'The <b>Operating system</b> is smart. When it sees that the <b>RAM</b>
      is filling up, it tries to <color=#0b0><b>clear it out</b></color>.

      

      

      It
      asks programs if they are no longer <b>using</b> something, and so a <color=#0b0><b>piece
      of space is freed up</b></color>.

      

      

      Click on the garbage
      truck and delete unnecessary data from RAM!'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173922978652901376
    m_Localized: 'But beware: <b>more RAM</b> does not automatically mean the <color=#0b0><b>fastest
      computer</b></color>, but it often helps a lot when you are doing <color=#0b0><b>multiple
      things at once</b></color>.'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173922988907974656
    m_Localized: "Usually, the <b>more RAM</b> a computer has, the more things it
      can handle <b>at once</b>.\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\u25CF  you can have <color=#0b0><b>more
      programs and tabs</b></color> open in the browser,\r\n\u25CF  the computer
      <color=#0b0><b>stutters less</b></color> during demanding work,\r\n\u25CF 
      work is usually <color=#0b0><b>smoother</b></color> (especially in games, video
      editing, graphics)."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173923009661390848
    m_Localized: 'The difference between <b>RAM</b> and a <b>hard drive</b> is in
      their purpose:

      

      

      <b>RAM</b> is <color=#0b0><b>fast
      and temporary</b></color> (working) memory.

      

      

      <b>A
      hard drive / SSD</b> is <color=#0b0><b>long-term storage</b></color>: files
      and programs are stored there so they remain <color=#0b0><b>even after turning
      off</b></color>.'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173923027009032192
    m_Localized: It is a <color=#0b0><b><u>temporary memory</u></b></color>. Once
      you turn off the computer, the contents of the RAM are <color=#0b0><b>deleted</b></color>,
      because it needs <color=#0b0><b>electrical energy</b></color> to remember data.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173923036588822528
    m_Localized: 'It is also called <color=#0b0><b>operating memory</b></color>.
      It''s a fast memory that the computer uses like a "work desk".

      

      

      When
      you are doing something (open a game, browser, document), the computer <color=#0b0><b>temporarily
      stores important things in RAM</b></color> so it has <color=#0b0><b>fast access</b></color>
      to them and can work smoothly.'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173923046575460352
    m_Localized: 'What is RAM? '
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173923149470126080
    m_Localized: RAM
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173938918367055872
    m_Localized: HDD/SSD
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939219157372928
    m_Localized: 'Binary system '
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939257489117184
    m_Localized: "Let's try it out \r\nin the game."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939283107926016
    m_Localized: 'Once you try this a bit, it will make sense why the <color=#0b0><b>binary
      system</color></b> is so important to a computer: its <color=#0b0><b>logic
      circuits</color></b> constantly work with <color=#0b0><b>values 0 and 1</color></b>,
      meaning whether something is <color=#0b0><b>off or on</color></b>, whether
      the <color=#0b0><b>current is flowing or not</color></b>. From these simple
      <color=#0b0><b>"yes/no" decisions</color></b>, the computer then builds everything
      else - numbers, text, images, sound, and games.'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939324069498880
    m_Localized: Try it yourself!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939348987858944
    m_Localized: And this is 4!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939381313359872
    m_Localized: Wrong answer!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939416474210304
    m_Localized: Wrong answer!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939428482502656
    m_Localized: This is 3!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939453715435520
    m_Localized: This is a number in <color=#0b0><b>binary notation</color></b>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939480282157056
    m_Localized: Zero is 0, one is 1. That's clear. But what about two?
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939508925059072
    m_Localized: We also sometimes call it the <color=#0b0><b>base-2 system</color></b>,
      because it only uses <color=#0b0><b>two numbers</color></b> - <color=#0b0><b>one
      and zero</color></b>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939522644627456
    m_Localized: Try it out!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939531951788032
    m_Localized: When the <color=#0b0><b>electric current flows</color></b>, we can
      count it as a <color=#0b0><b>value of 1</color></b>. When the <color=#0b0><b>current
      does not flow</color></b>, we take it as <color=#0b0><b>0</color></b>. And
      because computers can reliably distinguish these two options, they work in
      the so-called <color=#0b0><b>binary system</color></b>, which only uses the
      <color=#0b0><b>digits 0 and 1</color></b>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939560032653312
    m_Localized: 'Think of it as a special language that computers "speak".  '
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939571713789952
    m_Localized: "A computer doesn't think like a human. \r\nActually, it only recognizes
      two things: \r\n<color=#0b0><b>on or off</b></color> "
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939583709499392
    m_Localized: 'What is the binary system? '
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939590831427584
    m_Localized: How are numbers written?
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939624138395648
    m_Localized: This is a number in <color=#0b0><b>decimal notation</color></b>
      (as we know it).
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939695110213632
    m_Localized: This is 2!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939720175374336
    m_Localized: This is 1!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939743390846976
    m_Localized: In a <color=#0b0><b>binary number</b></color>, each <color=#0b0><b>digit</b></color>
      has its <color=#0b0><b>position (index)</b></color> and its value is calculated
      as <color=#0b0><b>2 to the power of that index</b></color>; when we <color=#0b0><b>sum</b></color>
      these values based on where the <color=#0b0><b>one</b></color> is, we get the
      <color=#0b0><b>final number</b></color>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173939771526238208
    m_Localized: Wrong answer!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940123113771008
    m_Localized: ... and often also the <color=#0b0><b>graphics card</b></color>....
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940131619819520
    m_Localized: 'Why does a computer need cooling? '
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940140377526272
    m_Localized: When a computer works, its components...
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940149630160896
    m_Localized: "Let's try it out \r\nin the game."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940157930688512
    m_Localized: "When the cooling doesn't work properly, many things can happen,
      such as:\r\n\r\n\u25CF  components may automatically <color=#0b0><b>slow down</b></color>
      (to not heat up as much),\r\n\r\n\u25CF  the computer may <color=#0b0><b>freeze</b></color>,\r\n\r\n\u25CF 
      it may <color=#0b0><b>restart or shut down</b></color>,\r\n\r\n\u25CF  during
      long-term overheating, components can even get <color=#0b0><b>damaged</b></color>"
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940165769842688
    m_Localized: The problem can also be caused by <color=#0b0><b>dust in the fans</b></color>.
      It blocks airflow, makes the fan turn slower, and heat is then dissipated poorly.
      The computer therefore <color=#0b0><b>overheats</b></color> faster. That is
      why it is important to clean the fans regularly and <color=#0b0><b>not block
      the ventilation openings</b></color>, especially on laptops.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940172417814528
    m_Localized: Sometimes a <color=#0b0><b>temperature warning</b></color> appears,
      or the computer behaves <color=#0b0><b>weirdly</b></color>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940177400647680
    m_Localized: The computer is <color=#0b0><b>hot to the touch</b></color> (especially
      laptops)
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940184925229056
    m_Localized: The fan is <color=#0b0><b>humming</b></color> or constantly running
      at <color=#0b0><b>full speed</b></color>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940194018480128
    m_Localized: "The computer will often \r\n\"tell\" you itself: "
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940215694643200
    m_Localized: 'How do you know if the computer''s cooling isn''t enough? '
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940229460348928
    m_Localized: ...and also rendering video, streaming and playing at the same time,
      or running <color=#0b0><b>demanding programs</b></color>. At that moment, the
      components <color=#0b0><b>heat up the most</b></color>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940238620708864
    m_Localized: The biggest load is typically when <color=#0b0><b>playing demanding
      games</color></b>...
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940247168700416
    m_Localized: '...they consume electrical energy and part of it <color=#0b0><b>turns
      into heat</b></color>. Cooling takes the heat away so the components <color=#0b0><b>don''t
      overheat</b></color> and work correctly.

      

      

      Watch how
      a gradual change in <color=#0b0><b>fan speed</b></color> affects the <color=#0b0><b>temperature</b></color>
      of individual components.'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940255158849536
    m_Localized: ... mainly the <color=#0b0><b>CPU</b></color> ...
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940264600227840
    m_Localized: The game or program starts to <color=#0b0><b>stutter and slow down</b></color>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940279678750720
    m_Localized: Cooling
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940334821265408
    m_Localized: Load
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940441125900288
    m_Localized: 'When you start a game or open a website, the <color=#0b0><b>CPU</color></b>
      constantly processes commands like: <color=#0b0><b>"load data"</color></b>,
      <color=#0b0><b>"calculate this"</color></b> or <color=#0b0><b>"send the result
      on"</color></b>. It''s millions of small steps that make up everything you
      see on the screen!'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940466681794560
    m_Localized: The wizard has a shield
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940479252123648
    m_Localized: "Let's try it out \r\nin the game."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940485438722048
    m_Localized: "Does the wizard have enough mana\r\nto conjure a shield?\r\n If
      so, create it."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940518670192640
    m_Localized: Spell cost
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940526001836032
    m_Localized: It will try to save itself by <color=#0b0><b>slowing down</color></b>
      so that it doesn't heat up as much. If that's not enough, the computer may
      <color=#0b0><b>freeze</color></b>, restart, or completely <color=#0b0><b>shut
      down</color></b> so the processor doesn't get damaged. That is why computers
      have <color=#0b0><b>cooling</color></b>, such as a metal cooler and a <color=#0b0><b>fan</color></b>.
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940536659562496
    m_Localized: Show shield
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940544498716672
    m_Localized: "To keep up with all this, it works to the rhythm of so-called <color=#0b0><b>clock
      cycles</color></b> - it's like a metronome or a heartbeat. \r\n\r\n<color=#0b0><b>Clock
      rate</color></b> tells us how many steps the CPU can handle in <color=#0b0><b>one
      second</color></b>. \r\n\r\nThe higher it is, the faster it ticks, but remember
      - the overall <color=#0b0><b>speed of a computer</color></b> also depends on
      other things!"
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940551381569536
    m_Localized: When the <color=#0b0><b>CPU</color></b> works hard, it starts to
      heat up. If the load is too high and it can't keep up without <color=#0b0><b>cooling</color></b>,
      the temperature can rise to a dangerous level. What happens then?
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940566271348736
    m_Localized: Clock rate is given in units of <color=#0b0><b>hertz (Hz)</color></b>,
      most commonly as <color=#0b0><b>gigahertz (GHz)</color></b>. For example, a
      processor with <color=#0b0><b>4 GHz</color></b> can handle an incredible <color=#0b0><b>4
      billion cycles</color></b> in a single second. That's pretty fast, right?
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940576773885952
    m_Localized: 'Inside the <color=#0b0><b>CPU</color></b> there is one more important
      thing: <color=#0b0><b>cache memory</color></b>. It''s a small but <color=#0b0><b>extremely
      fast</color></b> memory right on the processor, which serves as a <color=#0b0><b>stash</color></b>
      for the data the CPU needs right now. It uses it so it doesn''t have to constantly
      access the <color=#0b0><b>RAM</color></b>, which takes much <color=#0b0><b>longer</color></b>.'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940583124062208
    m_Localized: Cache
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940605685223424
    m_Localized: Remaining mana
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940627680153600
    m_Localized: Cache
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940637251555328
    m_Localized: A processor doesn't know what it will be cooking in the end, it
      just precisely follows commands <color=#0b0><b>one by one</color></b> in the
      exact order they are written. Just one bad step in the recipe and the whole
      program (or dinner) ends in an error!
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940644218294272
    m_Localized: "Each <color=#0b0><b>instruction</color></b> is <color=#0b0><b>one
      step</color></b> in a recipe - like \u201Aadd butter\u2018 or \u201Astir\u2018."
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940664380313600
    m_Localized: "It makes millions of tiny steps: it <color=#0b0><b>calculates</color></b>,
      <color=#0b0><b>compares</color></b> and <color=#0b0><b>controls</color></b>
      the rest of the computer.\r\n For instance, it tells the graphics what to draw,
      and the drive what to save...\r\nWithout it, not a single pixel moves!"
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940673087688704
    m_Localized: 'Imagine that the <color=#0b0><b>CPU</color></b> (processor) is
      like a chef and the program is its <color=#0b0><b>recipe</color></b>. '
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940685641240576
    m_Localized: 'What is a CPU? '
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940693119684608
    m_Localized: The CPU or <color=#0b0><b>processor</color></b> is very important
      in a computer. Its main function is to <color=#0b0><b>execute instructions</color></b>.
      What does that mean?
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940704670797824
    m_Localized: Prepare <color=red><b>100 g of butter</color></b>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940714527412224
    m_Localized: load <color="red"> MANA </color> into <color="red"> R1 </color>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940722031022080
    m_Localized: Add the <color=red><b>dough</color></b> <color=red><b>mix</color></b>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940730285412352
    m_Localized: load <color="red"> COST </color> into <color="red"> R2 </color>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940737206013952
    m_Localized: Prepare an empty <color=red><b>bowl</color></b>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940745133248512
    m_Localized: minus <color="red"> R1 </color> and <color="red"> R2 </color>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940754247471104
    m_Localized: Prepare <color=red><b>75ml of milk</color></b>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940774472404992
    m_Localized: move <color="red">MINUS</color> to <color="red">R2</color>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940787948703744
    m_Localized: Prepare <color=red><b>2 eggs</color></b>
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
  - m_Id: 173940795003523072
    m_Localized: '> 0 <color="red"> R2'
    m_Metadata:
      m_Items: []
